Next hook in the natural learning order is useContext â€” this solves prop drilling and introduces shared/global state.

ğŸ§© useContext â€” FROM SCRATCH
1ï¸âƒ£ Problem first: Prop drilling

Imagine this tree:

App
 â””â”€ Dashboard
     â””â”€ Profile


You want to send user from App to Profile.

<App user={user}>
  <Dashboard user={user}>
    <Profile user={user} />
  </Dashboard>
</App>


âŒ Dashboard doesnâ€™t need user, but still receives it.

This is called prop drilling.

2ï¸âƒ£ What is Context?

Context allows you to share data globally without passing props manually at every level.

3ï¸âƒ£ Basic steps of useContext

There are 3 steps (remember this for interviews):

Create context

Provide value

Consume value

4ï¸âƒ£ Step 1: Create context
import { createContext } from "react";

const UserContext = createContext(null);

5ï¸âƒ£ Step 2: Provide context value
function App() {
  const user = { name: "Shubham" };

  return (
    <UserContext.Provider value={user}>
      <Dashboard />
    </UserContext.Provider>
  );
}

6ï¸âƒ£ Step 3: Consume context using useContext
import { useContext } from "react";

function Profile() {
  const user = useContext(UserContext);

  return <h1>Hello {user.name}</h1>;
}

7ï¸âƒ£ Whatâ€™s happening internally?

React stores user at Provider level

Any child can read it

If value changes â†’ all consumers re-render

8ï¸âƒ£ Very important rules âš ï¸
âŒ Cannot use context outside Provider
useContext(UserContext); // undefined or default value

âŒ Context is NOT a state manager

It does not replace:

Redux

Zustand

useReducer (sometimes)

Context is for read-heavy, write-light data.

9ï¸âƒ£ Common use cases

Auth (currentUser)

Theme (dark/light)

Locale

Permissions

ğŸ”Ÿ Context + state (real-world)
const AuthContext = createContext();

function AuthProvider({ children }) {
  const [user, setUser] = useState(null);

  return (
    <AuthContext.Provider value={{ user, setUser }}>
      {children}
    </AuthContext.Provider>
  );
}


Consume:

const { user, setUser } = useContext(AuthContext);

ğŸ§  Mental model

Think of context as:

A global variable scoped to a component tree

ğŸ¯ Interview questions

Q: When should you NOT use context?
A: For frequently changing data â†’ causes re-renders.

Q: Does context replace Redux?
A: No, context handles sharing, Redux handles complex state logic.

Rails analogy ğŸ§ 

| React    | Rails               |
| -------- | ------------------- |
| Context  | `CurrentAttributes` |
| Provider | Controller setup    |
| Consumer | View / helper       |

ğŸ”‘ Summary

useContext avoids prop drilling

Needs Provider

Triggers re-render on value change

Best for global config/auth data